  <graph edgedefault="undirected">
    <node id="STREAMS">
      <data key="d0">CONCEPT</data>
      <data key="d1">The entity "STREAMS" refers to the flow of data or information, which can be related to various contexts such as content streaming, viewer activity, customer activity, or transactions. STREAMS have unique identifiers and are associated with multiple attributes, including customer IDs and content IDs. This suggests that STREAMS can be used to track and analyze different types of data flows, providing valuable insights into user behavior, content performance, and business transactions. Overall, the entity "STREAMS" plays a crucial role in capturing and organizing data from diverse sources, enabling informed decision-making and data-driven strategies.</data>
      <data key="d2">d4c32cb337d90fe6c32a1507c69b61b3,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAM_ID">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">A unique identifier for each stream, used to track and analyze stream information&gt;</data>
      <data key="d2">dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CUSTOMER_ID">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The CUSTOMER_ID entity serves as a unique identifier for each customer, utilized to join tables and track customer information across various datasets. This identifier is specifically assigned to the customer who has streamed content, enabling the joining of tables and facilitating the tracking of customer information. In essence, the CUSTOMER_ID plays a crucial role in linking customer data and streamlining the analysis of customer interactions, thereby providing a comprehensive understanding of customer behavior and preferences. By leveraging the CUSTOMER_ID, data architects can design efficient database structures and perform in-depth data analysis to uncover valuable insights into customer trends and patterns.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTENT_ID">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The CONTENT_ID entity serves as a unique identifier for each content item, enabling the tracking and analysis of content information. This identifier is utilized to join tables and facilitate the monitoring of content information, particularly in scenarios where content has been streamed. By leveraging the CONTENT_ID, it becomes possible to consolidate and examine data from various sources, ultimately providing a more comprehensive understanding of content performance and usage patterns. The CONTENT_ID's dual role in both identifying content and facilitating data analysis underscores its significance in data modeling and database design, particularly in the context of data warehousing development and SQL instruction.</data>
      <data key="d2">d4c32cb337d90fe6c32a1507c69b61b3,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAM_DATE">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The date when the streams occurred, used for tracking and analysis&gt;</data>
      <data key="d2">dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAM_TIME">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The time when the streams occurred, used for tracking and analysis&gt;</data>
      <data key="d2">dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAM_DURATION">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The duration of the streams in minutes, used for tracking and analysis&gt;</data>
      <data key="d2">dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STREAM_RATING">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The rating given to the streams by the customer, used for tracking and analysis&gt;</data>
      <data key="d2">dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">ATTRIBUTE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CUSTOMER">
      <data key="d0">CONCEPT</data>
      <data key="d1">The CUSTOMER entity refers to an individual who has either signed up for a service, purchased a product, or streamed content, thereby establishing a unique relationship with the organization. This individual is assigned a unique identifier, which distinguishes them from other customers and enables the organization to track their interactions, preferences, and behaviors. The CUSTOMER entity encompasses various attributes that provide a comprehensive understanding of their characteristics, needs, and activities, allowing for personalized services, targeted marketing, and data-driven decision-making. By analyzing the CUSTOMER entity, organizations can gain valuable insights into their target audience, tailor their offerings to meet specific needs, and foster long-term relationships built on trust, satisfaction, and loyalty.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">CONCEPT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTENT">
      <data key="d0">CONCEPT</data>
      <data key="d1">The CONTENT entity refers to a unique piece of media, such as a movie, TV show, or documentary, which possesses its own distinct attributes and characteristics. This entity represents the material that was streamed, and is identifiable by a unique identifier. Additionally, the CONTENT entity encompasses other attributes that further describe and define its properties. Overall, the CONTENT entity serves as a comprehensive representation of a singular media item, incorporating both its inherent characteristics and its role as a streamed material.</data>
      <data key="d2">d4c32cb337d90fe6c32a1507c69b61b3,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
      <data key="d3">CONCEPT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TABLE_NAME">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The entity "TABLE_NAME" refers to the name of a table, specifically identified as "Streams", which serves as a unique identifier for the table and its contents, including its attributes. This name is crucial in distinguishing the table and its purpose within a larger database structure, allowing for efficient data management and analysis. The "TABLE_NAME" entity, in this case, "Streams", provides a clear and concise label that facilitates understanding and interaction with the table's data, enabling effective data modeling, database design, and data analysis.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLUMN_NAME">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The COLUMN_NAME entity refers to the name of the column, which serves as a unique identifier for the column, enabling the identification of its attributes and contents. This identifier is crucial in distinguishing the column and accessing its associated data, thereby facilitating efficient data management and analysis. The COLUMN_NAME entity plays a vital role in data modeling and database design, as it provides a clear and concise label for the column, making it easier to understand and work with the data. By using the COLUMN_NAME, users can effectively identify, access, and manipulate the column's attributes and contents, ultimately supporting a wide range of data-related tasks and operations.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DATA_TYPE">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The data type of the column, used to define the type of data stored in the column&gt;</data>
      <data key="d2">dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DESCRIPTION">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The "DESCRIPTION" entity is a crucial component that serves to provide context and understanding of a particular attribute. It is utilized to offer a concise explanation of the purpose and significance of a specific column, thereby facilitating a deeper comprehension of the data it represents. The "DESCRIPTION" entity plays a vital role in data modeling and database design, as it enables users to grasp the underlying structure and relationships within the data. By examining the descriptions associated with the "DESCRIPTION" entity, it becomes evident that its primary function is to furnish a brief yet informative summary of the column's purpose, ultimately enriching the overall understanding of the data. Furthermore, the "DESCRIPTION" entity is essential in data warehousing development, as it helps to establish a clear and consistent framework for organizing and analyzing complex data sets. Through its descriptive attributes, the "DESCRIPTION" entity provides a valuable resource for data analysis and interpretation, allowing users to extract meaningful insights and make informed decisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JOIN_CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The JOIN_CONDITION entity refers to a condition used to join tables, linking related data together. This condition is utilized to specify how to join the Streams table with other tables, effectively establishing relationships between them. In essence, the JOIN_CONDITION entity plays a crucial role in combining data from multiple tables, enabling the creation of more comprehensive and meaningful datasets. By defining the join condition, users can ensure that related data is properly linked, facilitating more accurate and informative data analysis. The JOIN_CONDITION entity is a fundamental component in database design and data warehousing, particularly in the context of SQL instruction, where it is used to merge and integrate data from various tables, including the Streams table, to produce a unified view of the data.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SAMPLE_DATA">
      <data key="d0">ATTRIBUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">The SAMPLE_DATA entity refers to a collection of information used to demonstrate the contents and structure of a table. This entity provides an example of the data stored in a column, serving as an illustrative tool to help understand the nature of the data being stored. The SAMPLE_DATA is utilized to offer a representative sample, allowing users to comprehend the type of information that can be found within the table, thereby facilitating a clearer understanding of the data's organization and composition. By examining the SAMPLE_DATA, one can gain insight into the format, content, and relationships between different data elements, ultimately enabling a more informed analysis and interpretation of the data as a whole.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae531614ad2754d6b083288c0595dfa5,dcf10bbfcd07ccf54a18b52e04a4d891</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TITLE">
